<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(1)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In accordance with the director compensation policy, each non-employee director, except for Ms.&nbsp;Chrapaty, Mr.&nbsp;Haldeman, Mr.&nbsp;Kern,
Mr.&nbsp;Morris and Mr.&nbsp;Rampell, was awarded an annual cash retainer of $80,000 on May&nbsp;13, 2015, the day following the KCG 2015 Annual Meeting. Ms.&nbsp;Chrapaty and Mr.&nbsp;Rampell, who became directors on December&nbsp;3, 2015, each
received a cash retainer of $35,288 on that date, which represents the annual cash retainer of $80,000 prorated for the period from December&nbsp;3, 2015 to the 2016 Annual Meeting. Mr.&nbsp;Haldeman did not receive an annual cash retainer in 2015.
Messrs. Kern and Morris have waived the right to receive any cash compensation for their service on the Board of Directors or any committees thereof. Amounts included in this column also represent cash retainers paid for service as a committee chair
and cash paid for attendance at committee meetings. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(2)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On May&nbsp;13, 2015, each non-employee director then serving on the Board, except for Mr.&nbsp;Haldeman, Mr.&nbsp;Kern and Mr.&nbsp;Morris, was
granted an award of 5,975 RSUs with an aggregate grant date fair value of $80,000. On May&nbsp;13, 2015, Mr.&nbsp;Haldeman was granted an award of 23,899 RSUs with an aggregate grant date fair value of $320,000. The aggregate grant date fair value
of the annual RSUs granted to the non-employee directors on May&nbsp;13, 2015 is based on $13.39, the average of the high and low price of a share of KCG Common Stock as quoted on the NYSE on the date preceding the date of grant. On December&nbsp;3,
2015, Ms.&nbsp;Chrapaty and Mr.&nbsp;Rampell were each granted an award of 6,212 RSUs with an aggregate grant date fair value of $80,000. Messrs. Kern and Morris have waived the right to receive any RSU awards as compensation for their service on
the Board of Directors or any committees thereof. Each RSU will vest one year from the date of grant or upon earlier retirement (age 72 as set forth in our Corporate Governance Guidelines) and will be settled in shares of KCG Common Stock upon
vesting. Amount shown represents the aggregate grant date fair value computed in accordance with Financial Accounting Standards Board&#146;s Accounting Standards Codification 718 Compensation-Stock Compensation (&#147;FASB ASC Topic 718&#148;).
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_28"></A>COMPENSATION AND RISK </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">KCG designs its compensation policies and practices in a way to support a strong risk management culture. KCG&#146;s
compensation program is designed to encourage its executive officers and employees to focus on KCG&#146;s short-term and long-term performance without incentivizing unnecessary or excessive risk-taking. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our KCG Holdings, Inc. Amended and Restated Equity Incentive Plan (our &#147;Equity Incentive Plan&#148;), which was most
recently approved at the annual meeting of stockholders held on May&nbsp;12, 2015, provides that, if at any time within two years after the date on which an employee exercises an option or stock appreciation award (&#147;SAR&#148;) or on which
restricted stock or RSUs vest (each, a &#147;Realization Event&#148;), the employee is (1)&nbsp;terminated for cause, (2)&nbsp;engages or has engaged in any activity that is in violation of a non-competition agreement, (3)&nbsp;violates or has
violated any confidential or proprietary information obligation the employee owes to KCG (including, but not limited to, obligations in any non-compete agreement, employment agreement, offer letter, employee handbook, non-disclosure agreement, Code
of Business Conduct or Ethics, equity award agreement or any other Company agreement signed by the employee that contains such obligations) and/or (4)&nbsp;engages in or has engaged in any act of fraud against KCG, the Compensation Committee may
require the employee to pay to KCG an amount equal to the gain he or she recognized from the Realization Event, determined on a gross basis, without reduction for taxes incurred and without regard to any subsequent change in the fair market value of
a share of KCG Common Stock. The Company also may cancel or adjust any award granted under the Equity Incentive Plan if KCG&#146;s financial statements on which the calculation of the award was based are subsequently restated, and the Compensation
Committee determines that such restated financial statements would have resulted in a smaller award, or no award, if such information had been known at the time the award was originally calculated. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition, the Board adopted a Compensation Recoupment Policy to maintain and enhance a culture that is focused on
integrity and accountability and that discourages conduct detrimental to the Company&#146;s sustainable growth. The Compensation Recoupment Policy provides that, in the event that the Company restates its financial statements, the Compensation
Committee may recoup from any executive officer the annual bonuses (regardless of whether such bonuses were paid or awarded in cash, equity or a combination thereof) earned during the three-year period preceding the date on which the Company files
restated financial statements with the SEC. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee believes that mitigating excessive
risk taking is an important component of the Company&#146;s compensation philosophy. Accordingly, as part of the Compensation Committee&#146;s oversight of the Company&#146;s executive compensation plans and practices, it considers factors such as
the balance of fixed compensation and discretionary compensation, the balance of short-term and long-term incentives, and appropriate risk-mitigating controls such as the Equity Incentive Plan&#146;s recapture and cancellation provisions and the
Compensation Recoupment Policy, to ensure that the Company&#146;s compensation framework is structured in a way that aligns with sound risk management and that does not create risks that are reasonably likely to have a material adverse effect on the
Company. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-19-
</FONT></P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Head of Global Execution Services and

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For selected biographical information with respect to Mr.&nbsp;Coleman, please refer
above to the biographical information of our directors. Selected biographical information with respect to the other executive officers is set forth below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Philip Allison</I></B> (40), Chief Executive Officer, KCG Europe Limited (&#147;KCG Europe&#148;) since September&nbsp;22, 2014, leads the operations and strategic direction for KCG&#146;s
agency-execution and market making businesses in Europe, as well as certain U.S.-based market making businesses. Previously, Mr.&nbsp;Allison spent 17 years at UBS Group AG, most recently as Global Head of Cash Equities and EMEA Head of Equities,
responsible for operations across more than 30 countries. Mr.&nbsp;Allison began his career at UBS in 1997 trading derivatives and index arbitrage strategies in the UK and, later, ETFs in the U.S. In 2002, Mr.&nbsp;Allison became responsible for
global statistical proprietary trading and client algorithmic trading in Europe. Mr.&nbsp;Allison expanded his responsibilities in 2006 to include automated market making and statistical model development for global cash equities. UBS appointed
Mr.&nbsp;Allison the Head of European Client Trading and Execution in 2008, responsible for cash, sales, portfolio and electronic trading in the region. In 2010 he became Global Head of Cash Equities, and additionally in March 2012, EMEA Head of
Equities, serving on the boards of UBS Ltd and the Association for Financial Markets in Europe. Mr.&nbsp;Allison has a degree in mathematics from Cambridge University.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>John McCarthy</I></B> (52), General Counsel and Corporate Secretary since the closing of the Mergers on
July&nbsp;1, 2013, focuses on a broad range of global corporate and regulatory matters for KCG. Previously, Mr.&nbsp;McCarthy was General Counsel of GETCO, which he joined in 2006, through the closing of the Mergers. Prior to 2006, Mr.&nbsp;McCarthy
served as associate director at the Securities and Exchange Commission, where he led the Office of Compliance Inspections and Examinations in the Market Oversight unit, which was responsible for regulatory oversight of trading on stock and options
exchanges. Prior to his position with the SEC, Mr.&nbsp;McCarthy clerked for the Court of Special Appeals of Maryland. Mr.&nbsp;McCarthy earned a B.S. in Engineering and an A.B. in Economics from the University of Michigan, an M.Sc. in Finance from
the London School of Economics and a J.D. with Honors from the University of Maryland.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Nick Ogurtsov</I></B> (38), Chief Risk Officer since the closing of the Mergers and Chief Operating Officer since
August&nbsp;16, 2013, has more than 16 years of experience in leadership and financial markets. As Chief Operating Officer, he is responsible for overseeing KCG&#146;s operations and clearing. As Chief Risk Officer, he is responsible for managing
KCG&#146;s strategic and operational risk management framework, including the design and implementation of systems and processes to identify, mitigate and access KCG&#146;s risk exposure. Previously, Mr.&nbsp;Ogurtsov was the Chief Risk Officer of
GETCO until the closing of the Mergers. Prior to joining GETCO in<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-20-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>
</I></B>2012, Mr.&nbsp;Ogurtsov was Managing Director and Global Head of UBS&#146;s high-frequency electronic trading group, EMM Group. He built and managed EMM Group&#146;s global team in New
York, London and Tokyo, where they traded equities, fixed income and foreign exchange. As a member UBS&#146;s management team for the global cash equities business, Mr.&nbsp;Ogurtsov also helped rebuild UBS&#146;s trading technology in the
Asia-Pacific region. He began his career at SBC Warburg (subsequently merged into UBS) as a convertible bonds trader and later co-headed the equity-linked structured <B><I></I></B>products team. Mr.&nbsp;Ogurtsov received a B.S. in Physics and
Computer Science from Beloit College and a Master&#146;s degree in Computer Science from the University of Arizona.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Steffen Parratt</I></B> (52), Chief Financial Officer since January&nbsp;6, 2015, is responsible for all financial aspects of KCG. Mr.&nbsp;Parratt has more than 20 years of leadership experience in
financial services, technology and corporate strategy. Prior to becoming Chief Financial Officer of KCG, Mr.&nbsp;Parratt was an entrepreneur. During this time, he launched ventures in finance, management, and strategy, with a focus on developing
software to realize operational effectiveness and efficiencies. Previously, he was a Managing Director at Bank of America Merrill Lynch, where he helped develop a strategic plan to integrate Merrill Lynch, U.S. Trust and the legacy Bank of America
wealth business. Mr.&nbsp;Parratt also spent more than a decade at Citigroup Inc. in a number of management roles, most recently as Managing Director and Global Staff Functions Task Leader, Reengineering and Productivity Group, where he was
responsible for reengineering organizations and processes in the firm&#146;s finance, risk, compliance, audit, legal, human resources units. Mr.&nbsp;Parratt began his career as an engineer, and held positions at Sandia National Laboratories and
Hughes Aircraft Company. Mr.&nbsp;Parratt received an M.B.A. in Finance from The Wharton School. He received a Ph.D. and M.Sc. in Engineering from Cornell University. He earned his B.Sc. in Mechanical Engineering and a M.Sc. in Electrical
Engineering from the University of Rochester.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Ryan Primmer</I></B> (46), Global Head of
Quantitative and Systematic Trading, and previously Global Head of Fixed Income, Foreign Exchange and Commodities Trading from August 2013, currently oversees quantitative and systematic trading strategies for KCG. Mr.&nbsp;Primmer joined KCG in
August 2013 after more than 21 years at UBS and its predecessor firms. He began his career in 1991 at O&#146;Connor&nbsp;&amp; Associates in Chicago, Illinois, a market making firm focused on equity options, working as an options trader and market
maker. Mr.&nbsp;Primmer transitioned to trading convertible bonds and eventually spent time in London and New York where he was co-head of trading for the convertible bond desk. From 1999 to 2004, he led the expansion of the U.S. program and
quantitative trading business. From 2004 to 2008, Mr.&nbsp;Primmer was UBS&#146;s head of trading for U.S. equities until he was appointed during the financial crisis to lead the efforts to dissolve the company&#146;s mortgage asset portfolios and
help establish and lead the UBS&#146;s fund management team for StabFund. From 2009 to 2012, Mr.&nbsp;Primmer was Global Head of Equities Proprietary Trading at UBS, overseeing fundamental and statistical strategies. Just prior to joining KCG, he
was Global Head of Equities Trading at UBS. Mr.&nbsp;Primmer received a B.A. in Economics from Lawrence University in Appleton, Wisconsin.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Jonathan Ross </I></B>(47), Chief Technology Officer since the closing of the Mergers on July&nbsp;1, 2013, is responsible for all of KCG&#146;s technology operations and infrastructure.
Mr.&nbsp;Ross has more than 13 years of experience in financial technology and leadership. Previously, Mr.&nbsp;Ross was Chief Technology Officer of GETCO, which he joined in 2007, through the closing of the Mergers. Prior to becoming Chief
Technology Officer, he was head of GETCO Execution Services in Europe, where he oversaw order management, execution and technology solutions for European clients. Prior to joining GETCO, Mr.&nbsp;Ross was the Chief Technology Officer of the NASDAQ
Stock Market (&#147;NASDAQ&#148;) following its acquisition of Inet ATS in December of 2005. While at NASDAQ, Mr.&nbsp;Ross led the &#147;Single Book&#148; integration of INET, Brut and NASDAQ&#146;s SuperMontage into a single platform and oversaw
NASDAQ&#146;s initial implementation of Regulation NMS. Prior to his position at NASDAQ, Mr.&nbsp;Ross was the Chief Technology Officer of Inet ATS, Inc., where he also previously served as First Vice President of Technology, in charge of
development and maintenance of INET&#146;s core trading platform. He held the same position at the Island ECN, which was acquired by Instinet Group Inc. in 2002. Mr.&nbsp;Ross also has more than 15 years of experience in the software and technology
industries.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-21-

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Greg Tusar </I></B>(47), Head of Global Execution Services and
Platforms since August 2013, is responsible for KCG&#146;s sales, products and platforms globally. Mr.&nbsp;Tusar joined KCG in August 2013 from Goldman Sachs, where he spent 13 years, most recently as a partner and global head of the firm&#146;s
equities electronic trading business. Mr.&nbsp;Tusar helped Goldman Sachs expand its electronic trading franchise. Mr.&nbsp;Tusar was previously a limited partner at Spear, Leeds and Kellogg (&#147;SLK&#148;), when Goldman Sachs acquired the firm in
2000. He also worked for seven years at TLW Securities, most recently as its Chief Executive Officer, before it was acquired by SLK in 1999. He began his career at Mentor Graphics, an electronic design automation firm. Mr.&nbsp;Tusar is a member of
the board of directors of Per Scholas, a national nonprofit organization providing technology education and job placement in low-income communities.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="100%"></TD></TR>


<TR BGCOLOR="#dff6fb">
<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_31"></A>PROPOSAL 2&#151;ADVISORY APPROVAL OF</B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>2015 COMPENSATION OF NAMED EXECUTIVE OFFICERS</B></FONT></P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act requires public companies
to provide their stockholders with an advisory vote to approve executive compensation at least once every three years. We are providing this stockholder advisory vote on our executive compensation in accordance with Section&nbsp;14A of the Exchange
Act and Exchange Act Rule 14a-21(a). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This proposal, commonly known as a &#147;Say-on-Pay&#148; proposal,
gives stockholders the opportunity to endorse or not endorse our executive pay program and policies. At the annual meeting of Knight stockholders in 2011, Knight stockholders approved a proposal to hold a stockholder advisory vote on executive
compensation every year. As the successor to Knight, we will hold an advisory vote every year until the next stockholder vote on the frequency of the advisory vote, which we expect will occur on or before our 2017 annual meeting of stockholders.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_32"></A>Prior Say-on-Pay Vote </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our Board values our stockholders&#146; feedback and pays careful attention to communications from our stockholders
regarding the Company&#146;s executive compensation practices. Our executive compensation program is designed to pay for performance and to align the long-term interests of our named executive officers and other members of our management team with
the long-term interests of our stockholders, as discussed in more detail throughout this Proxy Statement. We believe these design and alignment principles help to ensure an appropriate balance between risk and reward; while our incentive
compensation arrangements do not encourage employees to take unnecessary or excessive risks, our employees are rewarded for executing on the Company&#146;s financial and strategic objectives. Further, the Compensation Committee and the Board of
Directors believe that the compensation policies and procedures articulated in this Proxy Statement are effective in furthering KCG&#146;s achievement of short-term and long-term business goals, and that the compensation of our named executive
officers reported in this Proxy Statement, which is structured to motivate superior individual performance, has supported and contributed to KCG&#146;s success. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">At our 2015 Annual Meeting, our advisory vote to approve named executive officer compensation continued to receive the
strong support of our stockholders (approximately 88% of votes cast). Based on the results of last year&#146;s Say-on-Pay vote as well as feedback we received from key stockholders over the course of 2015, our Compensation Committee determined to
keep the structure of our executive compensation program for 2016 substantially similar to the structure of the executive compensation program for 2015, and to incorporate certain changes we believe are consistent with our core compensation
philosophy of paying for performance. These changes, which include the introduction of return on equity as a component of the &#147;Performance Portion&#148; of the annual incentive award for certain of our NEOs and a rebalancing of the weighting of
the &#147;Performance Portion&#148; and &#147;Initiative Portions&#148; of the 2016 annual incentive award for each of Messrs. Coleman and Parratt, are described in the &#147;Compensation Program Highlights for 2016&#148; section of the Compensation
Discussion and Analysis below. As we continue to refine our compensation program, policies and practices going forward, we will continue to consider stockholder feedback. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_33"></A>2016 Say-on-Pay Advisory Vote </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In
accordance with Section&nbsp;14A of the Exchange Act, we are asking our stockholders to vote on the resolution set forth below. Your vote on this resolution is an advisory vote. The Compensation Committee is not required by law to take any action in
response to the stockholder vote. However, the Compensation Committee values our stockholders&#146; opinions, and the Compensation Committee intends to evaluate the results of the vote carefully when making future decisions regarding compensation of
the named executive officers. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-23-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_34"></A>Resolution </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board of Directors recommends that stockholders approve the following resolution: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:8%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">RESOLVED, that the stockholders approve the 2015 compensation of the named executive officers, as disclosed in this Proxy
Statement pursuant to Item&nbsp;402 of Regulation S-K, including the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis,&#148; the compensation tables and related disclosure. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_35"></A>Recommendation of the Board </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Board of Directors unanimously recommends that you vote &#147;<U>FOR</U>&#148; approval of the 2015 compensation of
our named executive officers, as disclosed in this Proxy Statement. </B></FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-24-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_36"></A>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_37"></A>COMPENSATION DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_38"></A>Executive Summary </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This
Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis describes the overall approach to the Company&#146;s executive compensation policies and practices for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, with a specific focus on the compensation program for our named
executive officers or &#147;NEOs&#148;: Daniel Coleman, Steffen Parratt, Sean Galvin, Philip Allison, Ryan Primmer, Greg Tusar and George Sohos. Although Mr.&nbsp;Sohos ceased providing service to the Company in March 2015, and Mr.&nbsp;Galvin
transitioned back to his role as the Company&#146;s Chief Accounting Officer in connection with Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s January&nbsp;6, 2015 appointment as the Company&#146;s Chief Financial Officer, both Mr.&nbsp;Sohos and Mr.&nbsp;Galvin are
considered NEOs for fiscal 2015 pursuant to the SEC&#146;s rules regarding proxy disclosure. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In 2015, our
NEOs and the other members of our management team continued to build an intermediary firm capable of directly addressing the need for liquidity across the global securities markets through principal trading as a market maker and agency-based
trading. As part of these efforts, KCG continued to focus on core businesses, reduce operating expenses and dispose of non-core businesses (including the sale of Hotspot in the first quarter of 2015). While market conditions, macro events and
competitive pressures in U.S. equities resulted in a more difficult operating environment for KCG market making in 2015, the Company initiated a more fundamental reengineering of operations as the year came to a close. KCG continues to focus on
reducing costs and executing on the capital return program in 2016 as the Company works to achieve a double-digit return on equity in 2017. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For the 2015 performance year, the individual and firm-wide performance metrics used by the Compensation Committee to make annual incentive compensation decisions were designed to focus management on the
Company&#146;s strategic objectives for 2015. Specifically, the portion of the 2015 annual incentive award based on the achievement of Company financial performance goals (the &#147;Performance Portion&#148;) was tied to return on tangible equity
and earnings per share for Mr.&nbsp;Coleman and Mr.&nbsp;Parratt, and for Messrs. Allison, Tusar and Primmer, our NEOs who lead business lines, a combination of consolidated earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization
(&#147;EBITDA&#148;) and business unit net trading revenue achievement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Consistent with the Company&#146;s
focus on achieving a double-digit return on equity, the Compensation Committee further refined the applicable metrics for the Performance Portion of the 2016 annual incentive award, replacing business unit measures with a return on equity component
for each of Messrs. Allison, Tusar and Primmer. Separately, the Compensation Committee rebalanced the weighting of the Performance Portion and the portion of the 2016 annual incentive award based on the achievement of individual initiatives (the
&#147;Initiatives Portion&#148;) for each of Messrs. Coleman and Parratt, so that a greater percentage of Messrs. Coleman and Parratt&#146;s award determination for 2016 will be tied to Company financial performance goals; specifically, EBITDA and
return on equity. We believe these changes illustrate our commitment to paying for performance, one of our core compensation philosophies, because the addition of the return on equity metric for our NEOs and the increased weighting of the
Performance Portion for Messrs. Coleman and Parratt will continue to motivate our management team to execute on the Company&#146;s financial and strategic objectives, which, as a result, will deliver value to our stockholders. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-25-
</FONT></P>

<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="2"></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-left:4.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Recoupment of cash incentive and equity awards from executive officers in the event of
certain financial statement restatements and other events</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-left:4.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No excessive perquisites or benefits</FONT></P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_39"></A>2016 Compensation Program Highlights </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As a result of ongoing discussions with our Board, the Compensation Committee implemented the following changes to the
Company&#146;s annual incentive award program for 2016. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I></I></B><B><I>Performance Metric Alignment &#150; Return on Equity.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Similar to the metrics used for the
Performance Portion of the annual incentive award for Messrs. Coleman and Parratt, for purposes of 2016 annual incentive award determinations for each of Messrs. Allison, Primmer and Tusar, return on equity will replace the component of the
Performance Portion previously tied to business unit measures. The Compensation Committee believes use of the return on equity metric as a key component of making 2016 annual incentive award determinations is appropriate in light of the
Company&#146;s focus on achieving a double-digit return on equity. <B><I> </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I></I></B><B><I>Increased Performance Portion Weighting.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For 2016, the Compensation Committee rebalanced the
weighting of the Performance and Initiatives Portion of the 2016 annual incentive award for each of Messrs. Coleman and Parratt, so that as compared to 2015, a greater percentage of Messrs. Coleman and Parratt&#146;s award determination for 2016
will be tied to Company financial performance goals including return on equity and EBITDA, and a lesser percentage will be based on the Initiatives Portion. We believe that the increased weighting of the Performance Portion for Messrs. Coleman and
Parratt is consistent with our core compensation philosophy of paying for performance, and will continue to motivate our management team to execute on the Company&#146;s financial and strategic objectives, which as a result, will deliver value to
our stockholders.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-26-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_40"></A>COMPENSATION DECISION-MAKING PROCESS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_41"></A>Compensation Philosophy </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee believes KCG&#146;s compensation programs should support its business strategies and provide balanced incentives for achieving short-term and long-term business goals and
objectives. KCG designs compensation packages that are intended to align the long-term economic interests of KCG&#146;s executive officers with its stockholders&#146; interests while also providing appropriate awards to motivate superior individual
performance. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In making compensation decisions, the Compensation Committee utilizes the following principles
to ensure that our compensation structure is competitive and reflects our core values: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I></I></B><B><I>Pay for performance.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Provide a compensation framework that appropriately awards achievement of
the Company&#146;s financial and strategic objectives, supports the attainment of KCG&#146;s vision, business strategy and operating imperatives, while reinforcing KCG&#146;s business values and creating value over the long term.<B><I>
</I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I></I></B><B><I>Align compensation with stockholders&#146; interests.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Motivate management to achieve financial
and strategic goals by delivering a meaningful portion of incentive compensation in equity awards, which aligns employee interests with those of stockholders.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I></I></B><B><I>Mitigate excessive risk-taking.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ensure that our incentive compensation arrangements do not
encourage our employees to take unnecessary and excessive risks, including risks that threaten the value of the Company.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I></I></B><B><I>Attract and retain a talented leadership team.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Design an incentive compensation program that
allows the Company to attract and retain qualified employees, for whom competition is diverse and includes a variety of financial services and technology firms.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_42"></A>Key Compensation Practices </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition to aligning executive pay with long-term stockholder interests, we are committed to good corporate governance practices and mitigation of inappropriate risk-taking. To further this commitment,
our 2015 compensation program had the following features: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I></I></B><B><I>Long-term ownership.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As discussed below under &#147;KCG Compensation Decisions for
2015&#151;Long-Term Equity Incentives,&#148; we granted unvested equity to executive officers following the Mergers to quickly align their interests with those of KCG stockholders. Additionally, a portion of the annual incentive award for 2015 was
paid to our named executive officers (other than Mr.&nbsp;Sohos) in the form of equity awards that are subject to market, cancellation and forfeiture risk over a multi-year period.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I></I></B><B><I>Recoupment and forfeiture policies.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our named executive officers are subject to recoupment
policies that provide for the cancellation or clawback of cash incentive and equity awards in the event of, among other things, fraud and financial restatement.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I></I></B><B><I>Continued review of compensation program.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </I></B>Each year, our Compensation Committee reviews our
compensation program to ensure that executive pay is aligned with Company policies, long-term stockholder interests and sound risk policies.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_43"></A>Compensation Committee Role and Responsibility </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee determines each continuing named executive officer&#146;s compensation package in accordance with the terms of the named executive officer&#146;s employment agreement on an
annual basis and at times of promotions or other changes in responsibilities; however, because Mr.&nbsp;Galvin served in a temporary role as Interim Chief Financial Officer, the Compensation Committee did not determine his compensation during the
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-27-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
interim period in which he served. The Compensation Committee may review market data, such as pay data from proxy statements and other sources, as a reference point for evaluating the relative
competitiveness of the compensation packages offered to the named executive officers. The Compensation Committee has also retained Pay Governance to act as its compensation consultant to provide advice and guidance on executive compensation matters
and, with respect to named executive officers other than the CEO, considers recommendations from the&nbsp;CEO. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In making compensation decisions for the targeted total compensation opportunity for each of the named executive
officers, the Compensation Committee considers each element of each named executive officer&#146;s compensation package and the total compensation that the named executive officer may be eligible to receive. Multiple factors may be considered in
determining the amount of total compensation to award the named executive officers each year. These factors may include: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="9%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">the present and future value of any equity-based awards that are granted during the year; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="9%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">alignment of short-term and long-term performance of KCG with variable elements of targeted total compensation; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="9%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">internal pay equity considerations; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="9%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">the relative competitiveness of KCG&#146;s compensation packages to the market generally. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_44"></A>Risk </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As described in the Compensation and Risk section of this Proxy Statement, our Compensation Committee believes that the mitigation of excessive risk-taking is an important component of the Company&#146;s
compensation philosophy, and reviews our compensation plans, including the plans in which each of our named executive officers and other members of our management committee participate with this objective in mind. Given the risk-mitigating controls
such as the Equity Incentive Plan&#146;s recapture and cancellation provisions and our Compensation Recoupment Policy and other factors such as the balance of fixed and discretionary compensation and short-term and long-term incentives, we believe
that our compensation plans, arrangements and agreements with the named executive officers are well balanced and structured in a manner that does not encourage imprudent risk-taking that could threaten the Company&#146;s value. The Compensation
Committee believes that the Company&#146;s compensation framework aligns with sound risk management and that the Company&#146;s compensation plans, policies and practices do not encourage excessive risk taking that is reasonably likely to have a
material adverse effect on the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_45"></A>Role of Compensation Consultants </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Pay Governance was originally engaged to assist with establishing the Company&#146;s compensation programs after the
closing of the Mergers and continues to advise the Compensation Committee as needed on developing trends and best practices in executive compensation design. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_46"></A>2015 COMPENSATION </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_47"></A>Compensation
Elements </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Below we discuss 2015 compensation determinations for each of our named executive officers.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_48"></A>Ongoing Compensation Elements </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table outlines the primary components of compensation paid to each of our named executive officers for the
2015 performance year. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-28-
</FONT></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As noted above, Mr.&nbsp;Sohos was employed by the Company for a portion of
2015, and Mr.&nbsp;Galvin served as Interim Chief Financial Officer for a portion of 2015. Accordingly, the compensation paid to Messrs. Sohos and Galvin in respect of the 2015 performance year was structured differently from that described below to
reflect facts and circumstances of each named executive officer&#146;s individual employment status. Additional details regarding the compensation elements listed below and other features of our 2015 compensation program are described in more detail
under &#147;Compensation Decisions for 2015&#148; below, and the individual arrangements with each of our named executive officers are described under &#147;Agreements with Our Named Executive Officers.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><B>Component</B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" align="left"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><B>Role and Structure</B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" align="left"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD></TR>


<TR>
<TD VALIGN="middle" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px" BGCOLOR="#dff6fb"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g129066g10u40.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Base Salary</B></FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Intended to retain quality
executives by providing a reasonable level of financial stability and predictability</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" align="left">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Set by the Compensation Committee based on position, level of responsibilities and competitive market data, and determined in the context of the overall compensation package offered to the
executive</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" align="left">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Reviewed periodically in light of
performance, market data and Compensation Committee independent consultant advice</FONT></P></TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Annual Incentive Compensation</B></FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Variable compensation designed to reward the achievement of
annual financial and other corporate performance goals and personal performance</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" align="left">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<I>Performance Portion</I>:<B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;two-thirds</B> of annual
incentive compensation earned based on the achievement of Company financial performance goals established by the Compensation Committee</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<I>Initiatives Portion</I>:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<B>one-third</B> of annual incentive compensation earned based on the achievement of individual initiatives established by
the Compensation Committee in consultation with our CEO</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Earned awards are subject to the Compensation Recoupment Policy</FONT></P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt">
<TD HEIGHT="8" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px" BGCOLOR="#dff6fb">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="4" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="top" COLSPAN="3" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.20em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Restricted Stock Unit Component of Annual Incentive
Compensation</I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt">
<TD HEIGHT="8" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px" BGCOLOR="#dff6fb">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="2"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="2" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px" BGCOLOR="#dff6fb"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Annual variable compensation structured to (1) encourage
the achievement of longer-term performance goals, (2) create an ownership culture focused on long-term value creation for KCG&#146;s stockholders and (3) encourage proper risk-taking by balancing the short-term component of other compensation
elements</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" align="left">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>80%</B> of annual incentive
compensation payout for CEO</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>60%</B> of annual incentive compensation payout for other NEOs</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" align="left">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Vests over a three-year period; subject to market risk
and cancellation and forfeiture provisions under the Equity Incentive Plan and the Compensation Recoupment Policy</FONT></P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt">
<TD HEIGHT="8" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px" BGCOLOR="#dff6fb">&nbsp;</TD>

Compensation</I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt">

intended to provide executives an annual cash payout linked to Company and individual performance</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" align="left">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>20%</B> of annual incentive compensation payout for CEO</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>40%</B> of annual incentive compensation payout for other NEOs</FONT></P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_49"></A>Compensation Decisions for 2015 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Base Salaries </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In connection with the Mergers in
2013 and the related execution of employment agreements with certain members of our management team, the Compensation Committee determined an annual base salary of $500,000 for each of Messrs. Tusar, Primmer and Sohos was appropriate based on
competitive market data and each </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-29-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
named executive officer&#146;s position and level of responsibilities. At the same time, after reviewing competitive market data from our peer group, compensation survey data, and large global
banks in the context of Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s total compensation package, the Compensation Committee determined that an annual base salary of $1,000,000 was appropriate for Mr.&nbsp;Coleman. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The base salaries of Messrs. Coleman, Tusar and Primmer have not increased from the 2013 rates, and Messrs. Allison and
Parratt&#146;s base salaries were similarly established at &pound;350,000 and $500,000, in connection with the executives&#146; appointments in September 2014 and January 2015, respectively. Using the average of daily spot rates of $1.53 to &pound;1
for 2015, Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s annual base salary of &pound;350,000 converts to an annual base salary of $535,115, which is generally consistent with the base salary rate paid to the other members of our management team (other than
Mr.&nbsp;Coleman). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In recognition of the increased duties and responsibilities assumed by Mr.&nbsp;Galvin in
connection with his appointment as Interim Chief Financial Officer, the Compensation Committee determined it was appropriate to establish his base salary at a rate of $500,000 per year for the period that Mr.&nbsp;Galvin served as Interim Chief
Financial Officer. Upon the completion of his service as Interim Chief Financial Officer and the return to his role as the Company&#146;s Chief Accounting Officer, Mr.&nbsp;Galvin&#146;s base salary was reestablished at a rate of $275,000 per year.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Annual Incentives </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Messrs. Coleman, Parratt, Allison, Tusar and Primmer </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In the first quarter of 2015, the Compensation Committee structured the 2015 annual incentive awards for Messrs. Coleman, Parratt, Allison, Primmer and Tusar so that two-thirds of each executive&#146;s
target award was based on the achievement of KCG financial performance goals under the Performance Portion and one-third of the target award was based on the achievement of individual initiatives under the Initiatives Portion, with a potential
payout of up to 200% of the target award (except for Mr.&nbsp;Coleman, whose maximum award was capped at $9,000,000). The table below sets forth the target 2015 annual incentive award for each of Messrs. Coleman, Parratt, Allison, Primmer and Tusar.

<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Performance Portion</I>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For each of Messrs. Coleman and
Parratt, the Compensation Committee determined to use return on tangible equity and earnings per share as the metrics for determining the Performance Portion of the executives&#146; 2015 annual incentive award. In each case, the return on tangible
equity and earnings per share measures were adjusted to exclude (1)&nbsp;the impact of the sale of Hotspot to BATS Global Markets and (2)&nbsp;the impact of the management committee&#146;s annual incentive awards, which exclusion was necessary to
avoid the circularity of including such payments as a component of the target used to determine the achievement of such measure (as adjusted, &#147;Adjusted ROTE&#148; and &#147;Adjusted EPS,&#148; respectively). For each of Messrs. Allison, Primmer
and Tusar, our NEOs who lead business lines, the Compensation Committee determined to use Adjusted EBITDA and business unit net trading revenue achievement as the metrics for determining the Performance Portion of the executives&#146; 2015 annual
incentive award. <I> </I></FONT></P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For 2015, the Compensation Committee certified in the first quarter of 2016 that the
Adjusted ROTE and Adjusted EPS metrics were earned at 72% and 73%, respectively, resulting in a payout of the Performance Portion equal to 73% of target. Additionally, the Compensation Committee certified in the first quarter of 2016 that Adjusted
EBITDA was earned at 89% of target, which resulted in a payout for that component of the Performance Portion equal to 89% of target. Based on the net trading revenues for KCG Europe, which Mr.&nbsp;Allison oversees, the Quantitative and Systematic
Trading business unit, which Mr.&nbsp;Primmer oversees and the U.S. Global Execution Services and Platforms business unit, which Mr.&nbsp;Tusar oversees, the Compensation Committee determined that the payouts for each of those components of the
Performance Portion were earned at 76%, 70% and 86% of target, respectively. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Initiatives
Portion</I>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Initiatives Portion considered the named executive officers&#146; progress toward achieving specific objectives that reflect each officer&#146;s individual role at KCG as discussed below. The individual
initiatives for Mr.&nbsp;Coleman were established by the Compensation Committee, and the individual initiatives for Messrs. Parratt, Allison, Primmer and Tusar were established by the Compensation Committee in consultation with Mr.&nbsp;Coleman. In
determining the level of achievement of the Initiatives Portion for each named executive officer other than the CEO, our CEO met with each officer in early 2016 to review actual performance versus the objectives set under the Initiatives Portion,
and then made recommendations to the Compensation Committee based on his performance assessment, which the Compensation Committee considered in determining actual payout of the annual incentive awards. The Chairman of the Board of Directors and the
Chair of the Compensation Committee reviewed the CEO&#146;s self-performance assessment with respect to his Initiatives Portion objectives, and that assessment was considered by the Compensation Committee in determining the<I>
</I></FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-31-
</FONT></P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(1)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In connection with Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s appointment as Chief Financial Officer, the Company agreed that Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s annual incentive
award for 2015 would be no less than target, or $1,000,000. Accordingly, the Compensation Committee determined the amount of Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s 2015 annual incentive award based on this guarantee and did not otherwise consider the achievement
of the applicable metrics comprising each of the Performance Portion and Initiative Portion that otherwise would have been evaluated in connection with establishing the amount of Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s 2015 annual incentive award.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Mr.&nbsp;Galvin </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Galvin&#146;s annual incentive opportunity for 2015 was structured differently than that described above for Messrs. Coleman, Parratt, Allison, Primmer and Tusar. Consistent with the
Company&#146;s bonus program for non-executive officers, Mr.&nbsp;Galvin was eligible for a discretionary annual incentive award and did not have an annual incentive award target or pre-determined performance metrics because he returned to his prior
role of Chief Accounting Officer in connection with Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s appointment in early January 2016. Mr.&nbsp;Galvin&#146;s award was determined based on his guarantee because the Company guaranteed that the total compensation paid to
Mr.&nbsp;Galvin in respect of 2015 would be no less than the total compensation earned for 2013. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Mr.&nbsp;Sohos </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In light of Mr.&nbsp;Sohos&#146;s resignation in March 2015, he was not eligible to receive a 2015 annual incentive award.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Long-Term Equity Incentives </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company believes that long-term equity incentive awards are a key element of the Company&#146;s pay-for-performance compensation philosophy because they align the interests of our executives with
those of our stockholders by subjecting a significant portion of compensation to market risk over a multiple-year period. The RSUs granted to our executives are inherently performance-based and help to motivate individuals to execute on the
Company&#146;s long-term business strategy and to achieve strategic, financial and operational objectives because the value of these equity awards is directly dependent on the price of our stock. Additionally, equity awards such as our RSUs are an
important tool for deferring a substantial portion of compensation, which aids in retention and mitigates inappropriate short-term risk-taking. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In accordance with this component of the Company&#146;s pay-for-performance philosophy, the Company continued to award a meaningful portion of the 2014 annual incentive award earned by its executive
officers in the form of equity awards. As noted above, 80% of Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s 2015 annual incentive award was granted in the form of RSUs, with Messrs. Parratt, Allison, Primmer and Tusar receiving RSUs in respect of 60% of each
executive&#146;s 2015 annual incentive award. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-33-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For non-executive officer employees, the Company decided to pay 2015 annual
incentive awards partially in the form of equity if the employee earned an award of at least $250,000, with the equity portion of such award determined in accordance with a pre-established deferral scale. Mr.&nbsp;Galvin received 22% of his 2015
annual incentive award in the form of RSUs, which is consistent with the equity payout scale implemented by the Company for non-executive officers, because he was not an executive officer at the end of 2015. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition to being subject to market risk over a multi-year period, all RSUs granted to our named executive officers
are subject to recapture and cancellation provisions under the terms of our Equity Incentive Plan, as well as forfeiture provisions under our Compensation Recoupment Policy. For more details on the stock options, SARs and RSUs held by our named
executive officers, see &#147;Outstanding Equity Awards at Fiscal Year-End 2015&#148; below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>2015 Annual Incentive Compensation
Determinations </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In January 2016, based primarily on the factors discussed above, the Compensation
Committee approved the following annual incentive awards for Messrs. Coleman, Parratt, Galvin, Allison, Primmer and Tusar for their performance in fiscal year 2015. As discussed above, Mr.&nbsp;Sohos was not eligible for a 2015 annual incentive
award. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
