<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">$</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" ALIGN="right"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">2,763,735</FONT></TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="line-height:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000;width:10%">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(1)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Represents annual incentive awards paid under the Executive Incentive Plan. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(2)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Messrs. Coleman, Parratt, Galvin, Allison, Primmer and Tusar received 279,540, 57,143, 15,447, 190,365, 147,921 and 157,928 RSUs, respectively, in
each case, calculated using $10.50, the average of the high and low price of a share of KCG Common Stock as quoted on the NYSE on February&nbsp;2, 2016, the date preceding the date of grant (and rounding up to avoid fractionals).
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(3)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Does not include base salaries paid, the one-time sign-on award of RSUs granted to Mr.&nbsp;Parratt in January 2015, or the special one-time awards
granted to each of Messrs. Primmer and Tusar in February 2016 as further described in &#147;One-Time Awards,&#148; below. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>One-Time Awards </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company regularly makes off-cycle grants of RSUs in connection with promotions, new hires and for other purposes such as rewarding exemplary performance and for retaining key employees. In connection
with his appointment as Chief Financial Officer, the Compensation Committee approved a one-time award of RSUs for Mr.&nbsp;Parratt with a grant date value of $500,000. These RSUs were granted to Mr.&nbsp;Parratt on January&nbsp;6, 2015 and are
scheduled to vest in equal installments on each of the first three anniversaries of grant, subject to Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s continued employment with the Company. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Additionally, Messrs. Primmer and Tusar were granted special one-time awards of $500,000 and $250,000, respectively, in
the form of RSUs. These RSUs were granted at the same time as the grant of the equity component of the executive&#146;s 2015 annual incentive award and were approved by the Compensation Committee in recognition of the increased responsibilities and
oversight delegated to each NEO during 2015, as well as to recognize the role of Messrs. Primmer and Tusar in the leadership of the Company. These RSUs are scheduled to vest in equal installments on each of the first three anniversaries of grant,
subject to Messrs. Primmer&#146;s and Tusar&#146;s respective continued employment with the Company. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-34-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_50"></A>Compensation Program Highlights for 2016 </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee routinely reviews and discusses the Company&#146;s compensation programs to ensure that they
support its business strategies and provide balanced incentives for achieving short-term and long-term business goals and objectives. As a result of its ongoing review of the executive compensation programs for 2015 and ongoing discussions with the
Board, the Compensation Committee implemented the following changes for the 2016 performance year. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I></I></B><B><I>Performance Metric Alignment &#150; Return on Equity.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Similar to the metrics used for the
Performance Portion of the annual incentive award for Messrs. Coleman and Parratt, for purposes of 2016 annual incentive award determinations for each of Messrs. Allison, Primmer and Tusar, return on equity will replace the component of the
Performance Portion previously tied to business unit measures. The Compensation Committee believes use of the return on equity metric as a key component of making 2016 annual incentive award determinations is appropriate as the Company works towards
achieving a double-digit return on equity. <B><I> </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I></I></B><B><I>Increased Performance Portion Weighting.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For 2016, the Compensation Committee rebalanced the
weighting of the Performance and Initiatives Portion of the 2016 annual incentive award for each of Messrs. Coleman and Parratt, so that as compared to 2015, a greater percentage of Messrs. Coleman and Parratt&#146;s award determination for 2016
will be tied to Company financial performance goals including return on equity and EBITDA, and a lesser percentage will be based on the Initiatives Portion. We believe that the increased weighting of the Performance Portion for Messrs. Coleman and
Parratt is consistent with our core compensation philosophy of paying for performance, and will continue to motivate our management team to execute on the Company&#146;s financial and strategic objectives, which as a result, will deliver value to
our stockholders.<B><I> </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_51"></A>OTHER COMPENSATION AND BENEFITS ELEMENTS
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Retirement and Benefit Plans </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">KCG provides named executive officers with access to retirement and health and welfare programs, on the same terms and conditions as those made to salaried employees generally. Although the Company
sponsors a voluntary deferred compensation plan, a legacy Knight arrangement, none of our NEOs currently participates in such plan, nor do any of our NEOs have balances outstanding under such plan. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Perquisites </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our named executive officers generally are offered perquisites on the same basis as our general employee population. See the &#147;Summary Compensation Table&#148; set forth below for more information.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_52"></A>TAX CONSIDERATIONS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_53"></A>Section&nbsp;162(m) Tax Considerations </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Generally, Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Code imposes a $1 million limit on the amount that a public company may deduct for compensation paid to its chief executive officer and three other most highly
compensated officers, other than the chief financial officer, each year. This limitation does not apply to &#147;qualifying performance-based&#148; compensation as defined in the Code. The Compensation Committee has and will continue to emphasize
performance-based compensation for the named executive officers and will seek to minimize the impact of Section&nbsp;162(m); however, the Compensation Committee may not necessarily limit executive compensation to the amount deductible under
Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Code. In certain situations, the Compensation Committee may approve compensation that will not be deductible in order to ensure competitive levels of total compensation for the named executive officers or for other
reasons. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-35-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_54"></A>REPORT OF THE COMPENSATION COMMITTEE </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee, composed of independent directors, reviewed and discussed the above &#147;Compensation
Discussion and Analysis&#148; with KCG&#146;s management. Based on the review and its discussions, the Compensation Committee recommended to the Board of Directors that the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; be included in this Proxy
Statement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:54%; text-indent:-2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Compensation Committee </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:54%; text-indent:-2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">James T. Milde, Chairman </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:54%; text-indent:-2%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Rene Kern </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:54%; text-indent:-2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">John C. (Hans) Morris </FONT></P>

Sohos&#146;s performance during 2014. One-third of such RSU awards vested on February&nbsp;4, 2016 and the remainder will vest in equal installments on February&nbsp;4, 2017 and February&nbsp;4, 2018. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(7)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Includes a special one-time award of $300,000 granted in the form of RSUs at the same time as the grant of the equity component of the 2014 annual
incentive award, as described in (3)&nbsp;above. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:22px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_58"></A>AGREEMENTS WITH OUR NAMED
EXECUTIVE OFFICERS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_59"></A>Agreements with Mr. Coleman </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In connection with the closing of the Mergers, Mr.&nbsp;Coleman and KCG entered into an employment agreement, which
provides for Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s employment as CEO of KCG for a term of three years from the closing of the Mergers. During the term, the Board of Directors will continue to nominate Mr.&nbsp;Coleman to serve as a member of the KCG Board of
Directors unless prohibited by applicable law. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Coleman provides for,
among other things, an initial annual base salary of $1,000,000 and an annual incentive to be paid 80% in RSUs and 20% in cash, with a target of $5,000,000. Pursuant to the terms of his employment agreement, on July&nbsp;5, 2013 Mr.&nbsp;Coleman was
granted 1,700,000 stock options with an exercise price of $11.65 (the &#147;Initial Stock Options&#148;) and 1,700,000 performance SARs with an exercise price of $22.50 (the &#147;Initial Performance SARs&#148;). The Initial Stock Options and
Initial Performance SARs each have five-year terms and vest in three equal annual installments on each of the first three anniversaries of the grant date, subject to Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s continued employment. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Coleman will be subject to a covenant not to compete with KCG or its affiliates during his employment and for a
period of 12 months following his termination for any reason and to a covenant not to solicit employees during his employment and for a period of 36 months following his termination for any reason. If Mr.&nbsp;Coleman breaches the non-competition or
non-solicitation covenants, he must forfeit all unexercised Initial Stock Options and unexercised Initial Performance SARs (whether vested or unvested) and repay to KCG any gains that he received after the end of his employment both from the
exercise of such awards and from the vesting of any annual incentive paid in the form of equity. Following a change in control (as defined in the agreement), each of the non-competition period and non-solicitation period will be reduced to six
months following his termination for any reason. Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s obligation to comply with the non-competition and non-solicitation covenants survives the end of the term of the employment agreement. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">If Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s employment is terminated during the term of the employment agreement by KCG without cause or
by Mr.&nbsp;Coleman for good reason (each as defined in the agreement), subject to his execution of a release, Mr.&nbsp;Coleman will be entitled to receive: (i)&nbsp;subject to compliance with non-competition and non-solicitation covenants described
above, (a)&nbsp;continued vesting of his Initial Stock Options and Initial Performance SARs, (b)&nbsp;continued vesting of any annual incentive paid in the form of equity and (c)&nbsp;non-compete/non-solicit payments equal, in the aggregate, to
$2,000,000, paid in equal monthly installments over the course of his non-competition period described above; (ii)&nbsp;any earned but unpaid annual incentive for the fiscal year ending immediately before termination, paid 100% in cash;
(iii)&nbsp;an annual incentive for the fiscal year in which the </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-40-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
termination occurs, paid 100% in cash and prorated for the number of days elapsed during the year; and (iv)&nbsp;payment of COBRA health insurance premiums for up to 12 months following
termination. If Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s employment is terminated after the term of the employment agreement by KCG without cause or by Mr.&nbsp;Coleman for good reason, Mr.&nbsp;Coleman will be entitled to receive, subject to the same terms outlined
above, continued vesting of his Initial Stock Options, his Initial Performance SARs and any annual incentive paid in the form of equity and the non-compete/non-solicit payments. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On April&nbsp;17, 2014, KCG and Redmont Holdings LLC entered into an amended Aircraft Timesharing Agreement under which
Mr.&nbsp;Coleman will lease and operate his personal aircraft on behalf of KCG on a nonexclusive basis. KCG has agreed to reimburse Mr.&nbsp;Coleman at the rate of $5,000 per flight hour for use of his aircraft by employees of KCG, provided that
such amount does not exceed the maximum amount permitted to be charged under Section&nbsp;91.501(d) of the Federal Aviation Regulations, in which event the charge will be less. The amount charged in any single year may not exceed $125,000 without
the general approval of the Board. During 2015, KCG reimbursed Mr.&nbsp;Coleman in the amount of $19,750 for use of his personal aircraft by other employees of KCG. The Aircraft Timesharing Agreement has an initial term of one year and will continue
for additional periods of one year unless terminated by either party on 30 days&#146; written notice. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_60"></A>Employment
Agreements with Messrs. Parratt, Allison, Primmer and Tusar </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Mr.&nbsp;Parratt </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In connection with his January 2015 appointment as Chief Financial Officer, the Compensation Committee approved, and
authorized the Company to enter into, an employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Parratt. Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s employment agreement has an initial term of three years and thereafter renews automatically for successive one-year extension terms unless
either party gives notice of nonrenewal at least 90 days before the end of the applicable term. Mr.&nbsp;Parrat&#146;s employment agreement provides for, among other things: (i)&nbsp;an initial annual base salary of $500,000, (ii)&nbsp;an annual
incentive award, (iii)&nbsp;a sign-on award of $500,000 granted in the form of RSUs that vest in three equal installments on each of the first three anniversaries of the date of grant, subject to Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s continued employment and
(iv)&nbsp;a 2015 annual incentive award no less than 200% of the amount of Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s base salary. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Parratt is subject to a covenant not to compete with KCG or its affiliates during his employment and for a
period of six months thereafter and to a covenant not to solicit KCG&#146;s employees during his employment and for a period of 18 months following his termination of employment for any reason. If Mr.&nbsp;Parratt is terminated by KCG without cause
or by reason of his resignation for good reason (each as defined in the employment agreements), subject to the execution of a release, Mr.&nbsp;Parratt will be entitled to receive: (i)&nbsp;subject to compliance with non-competition and
non-solicitation covenants described above, (a)&nbsp;continued vesting of his sign-on award of RSUs, (b)&nbsp;continued vesting of any annual incentive paid in the form of equity and (c)&nbsp;non-compete/non-solicit payments equal, in the aggregate,
to $500,000, paid in equal monthly installments over the course of his non-competition period described above; (ii)&nbsp;any earned but unpaid annual incentive for the fiscal year ending immediately before termination, paid 100% in cash;
(iii)&nbsp;an annual incentive for the fiscal year in which the termination occurs, paid 100% in cash and prorated for the number of days elapsed during the year; and (iv)&nbsp;payment of COBRA health insurance premiums for up to 12 months following
termination. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Mr.&nbsp;Allison </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In connection with his appointment as Chief Executive Officer of KCG Europe Mr.&nbsp;Allison and KCG Europe entered into an employment agreement, pursuant to which Mr.&nbsp;Allison commenced employment
with KCG Europe effective September&nbsp;22, 2014. The employment agreement does not have a set term, but stipulates that Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s employment with KCG Europe will continue as per the terms of the employment agreement until either
party gives written notice of termination at least six months prior to the effective date of such </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-41-
</FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
termination. However, KCG Europe may, at its discretion, terminate Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s employment with immediate effect and pay Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s base salary over the six-month period
in lieu of giving advance notice of such termination. Additionally, KCG Europe may terminate Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s employment without notice and without any payment in lieu of notice if Mr.&nbsp;Allison is guilty of gross misconduct. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s employment agreement provides for, among other things: (i)&nbsp;an initial annual base salary of
&pound;350,000; (ii)&nbsp;subject to Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s employment in good standing through January&nbsp;31, 2015, a payment equal to $2,000,000 less the amount of base salary received in 2014, paid 60% in the form of KCG equity and 40% in cash
(the &#147;2014 Compensation Payment&#148;); and (iii)&nbsp;the one-time award of 750,000 Replacement RSUs, which was granted to Mr.&nbsp;Allison after he provided KCG with satisfactory documentation showing that he forfeited equity awards granted
by his previous employer in connection with his resignation of employment with such prior employer to join KCG. One-third of the Replacement RSUs vested on each of July&nbsp;1, 2015 and September&nbsp;22, 2015, with the remaining Replacement RSUs
scheduled to vest on September&nbsp;22, 2016, subject to Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s continued employment with KCG Europe. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During the term of his employment and for 12 months thereafter, Mr.&nbsp;Allison is subject to a covenant not to compete with KCG Europe and a covenant not to solicit customers, potential customers and
key employees of KCG Europe, provided, however, that the length of Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s required compliance with these non-competition and non-solicitation covenants will be reduced by any period of &#147;garden leave&#148; he is required by KCG
Europe to serve in connection with a termination of employment. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Messrs. Primmer and Tusar </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In January 2014, the Company entered into amended and restated employment agreements with each of Mr.&nbsp;Primmer and
Mr.&nbsp;Tusar. The employment agreements have an initial term of three years and thereafter renew automatically for successive one-year extension terms unless either party gives notice of nonrenewal at least 90 days before the end of the applicable
term. The employment agreements provide for, among other things: (i)&nbsp;an initial annual base salary of $500,000, (ii)&nbsp;an annual incentive award and (iii)&nbsp;for Mr.&nbsp;Primmer, a sign-on award of $3,600,000 granted in the form of RSUs
that vest in three equal installments on the first three anniversaries of Mr.&nbsp;Primmer&#146;s start date (Mr. Primmer&#146;s &#147;Performance Award&#148;). </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Each of Messrs. Primmer and Tusar is subject to a covenant not to compete with KCG or its affiliates during his
employment and for a period of six months thereafter and to a covenant not to solicit KCG&#146;s employees during his employment and for a period of 18 months following his termination of employment for any reason. If Mr.&nbsp;Primmer is terminated
by KCG without cause or by reason of his resignation for good reason (each as defined in the employment agreements), subject to the execution of a release and to his compliance with non-competition and non-solicitation covenants described above, he
will be entitled to receive: (i)&nbsp;full vesting of his Performance Awards, (ii)&nbsp;continued vesting of any annual incentive paid in the form of equity and (iii)&nbsp;non-compete/non-solicit payments equal, in the aggregate, to $1,000,000. If
Mr.&nbsp;Tusar is terminated by KCG without cause or by reason of his resignation for good reason (each as defined in the employment agreements), subject to the execution of a release and to his compliance with non-competition and non-solicitation
covenants described above, he will be entitled to receive: (i)&nbsp;full vesting of all outstanding equity awards and (ii)&nbsp;non-compete/non-solicit payments equal, in the aggregate, to the sum of (a)&nbsp;$500,000 and (b)&nbsp;75% of the cash
portion of the annual incentive award paid in respect of the fiscal year preceding the fiscal year in which Mr.&nbsp;Tusar&#146;s termination of employment occurs. Additionally, upon a termination by KCG without cause or by reason of resignation for
good reason, the employment agreements with Messrs. Primmer and Tusar entitle each to: (iii)&nbsp;any earned but unpaid annual incentive for the fiscal year ending immediately before termination, paid 100% in cash; (iv)&nbsp;an annual incentive for
the fiscal year in which the termination occurs, paid 100% in cash and prorated for the number of days elapsed during the year; and (v)&nbsp;payment of COBRA health insurance premiums for up to 12 months following termination </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-42-

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_61"></A>Letter Regarding Mr.&nbsp;Galvin&#146;s Appointment as Interim Chief Financial
Officer </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Galvin does not have an employment agreement with KCG; however, in connection with
Mr.&nbsp;Galvin&#146;s appointment as Interim Chief Financial Officer, KCG established Mr.&nbsp;Galvin&#146;s base cash salary for the period he served as Interim Chief Financial Officer at a rate of $500,000 per year and guaranteed that
Mr.&nbsp;Galvin&#146;s total compensation (base salary and annual incentive) for 2014 would be no less than the total compensation earned for 2013. Additionally, Mr.&nbsp;Galvin was granted a one-time award of 25,000 RSUs that vest ratably on each
of the three anniversaries of grant, subject to his continued employment. Mr.&nbsp;Galvin&#146;s base cash salary following his service as Interim Chief Financial Officer was established at a rate of $275,000, and the Company guaranteed that the
total compensation paid to Mr.&nbsp;
Galvin in respect of 2015 would be no less than the total compensation earned for 2013. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_62"></A>Separation Agreement with
Mr.&nbsp;Sohos </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On March&nbsp;30, 2015, KCG entered into a separation agreement (the &#147;Separation
Agreement&#148;) outlining the payments and benefits due to Mr.&nbsp;Sohos in connection with his resignation, which was effective as of March&nbsp;2, 2015. As was required by the Separation Agreement, during the period that commenced on
March&nbsp;2, 2015 and ended on September&nbsp;30, 2015 (the &#147;Garden Leave Period&#148;), Mr.&nbsp;Sohos generally kept the Company informed of his whereabouts so that he could be contacted if needed to perform such duties reasonably requested
by the Company. During the Garden Leave Period, during which Mr.&nbsp;Sohos complied with applicable non-competition covenants, Mr.&nbsp;Sohos continued to receive base salary payments at the rate in effect prior to his resignation and also remained
eligible to participate in the Company&#146;s benefit program on such terms as in effect prior to his resignation. Consistent with the terms of Mr.&nbsp;Sohos&#146;s prior employment agreement with KCG and in connection with Mr.&nbsp;Sohos&#146;s
compliance with applicable restrictive covenants during the Garden Leave Period, the Separation Agreement provided for, among other things, (1)&nbsp;continued vesting in the RSUs and stock options held by Mr.&nbsp;Sohos at the time of his
resignation as if his employment with the Company had continued through the Garden Leave Period and (2)&nbsp;non-compete/non-solicit payments in respect of a seven-month non-competition and 18-month non-solicitation covenants. See &#147;Potential
Payments on Termination or Change in Control&#148; below for additional information regarding the payments and benefits made to Mr.&nbsp;Sohos in connection with his departure. </FONT></P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" ROWSPAN="2" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000" BGCOLOR="#baedf7"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><B>Year&nbsp;of</B></FONT></P>

exercise price of $8.34. Also reflects (1)&nbsp;57,636 shares acquired on January&nbsp;31, 2015, with a fair market value per share of $12.17 on the vesting date; (2)&nbsp;67,991 shares acquired
on February&nbsp;5, 2015 with a fair market value per share of $12.474 on the vesting date; and (3)&nbsp;17,778 shares acquired on July&nbsp;1, 2015 with a fair market value per share of $12.417 on the vesting date. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_65"></A>POTENTIAL PAYMENTS UPON TERMINATION OR CHANGE IN CONTROL </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This section describes and quantifies the compensation and benefits to which each NEO would have been entitled under
existing plans, arrangements and agreements upon experiencing a termination of employment on December&nbsp;
31, 2015. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_66"></A>Payments and Benefits Upon a Termination or Change in Control </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Agreements with Our Named Executive Officers </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As discussed above, the agreements with our named executive officers provide certain payments and benefits on terminations of employment, including, in some cases, continued vesting of equity awards. The
agreements do not provide any &#147;single-trigger&#148; payments or benefits on a change in control. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Under
the terms of his Separation Agreement with the Company, Mr.&nbsp;Sohos received certain payments and benefits upon his termination of employment, the delivery of which were contingent on his execution of a general release of claims. The actual
payments and benefits to which Mr.&nbsp;Sohos became entitled under the terms of his Separation Agreement are described and quantified in the following narrative, and, consistent with the SEC&#146;s proxy disclosure rules, amounts payable to
Mr.&nbsp;Sohos upon other potential triggering events are not reflected in the table below because his employment with the Company terminated prior to December&nbsp;31, 2015. Pursuant to the Separation Agreement, during the Garden Leave Period,
Mr.&nbsp;Sohos received (1)&nbsp;seven months of base salary payments equal to $291,667 in the aggregate, (2)&nbsp;non-compete/non-solicit payments equal to $1,500,000, in the aggregate and (3)&nbsp;vesting in 17,778 RSUs and 32,659 options with an
exercise price of $8.24 on July&nbsp;1, 2015 (valued at $220,803 and $136,512, respectively, based on the closing price of KCG Common Stock on the NYSE on July&nbsp;1, 2015 vesting date ($12.42)). Additionally upon conclusion of the Garden Leave
Period, consistent with the terms of his prior employment agreement, Mr.&nbsp;Sohos continued to vest in the following RSUs that, as of such time remained unvested: 135,981 RSUs granted in January 2014 in respect of the 2013 annual incentive award,
108,089 RSUs granted in February 2015 in respect of the 2014 annual incentive award and 24,510 RSUs granted in February 2015 as part of a special one-time award. Mr.&nbsp;Sohos forfeited the remainder of his unvested equity awards upon conclusion of
the Garden Leave Period. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Effect of Termination Events or Change in Control on Unvested Equity Awards </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Equity awards held by our named executive officers as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 are subject to the terms of the Equity
Incentive Plan and are each governed by an award agreement evidencing such award. The award agreements set forth the terms and conditions of the respective award and, among other things, outline the effect of various termination events on the
vesting and delivery of unvested equity awards. The award agreements evidencing the named executive officers&#146; outstanding equity awards as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, provide for &#147;double-trigger&#148; vesting upon a change in control (as
defined in the Equity Incentive Plan), and this treatment is consistent with the change in control provision applicable to all awards granted to participants under our Equity Incentive Plan in 2013, 2014, 2015 and to-date in 2016. In the event the
employment of an Equity Incentive Plan participant (including our NEOs) is terminated without &#147;cause&#148; or, if applicable, resigns with &#147;good reason&#148; (as each such term is defined below) within 12 months following a change in
control (a &#147;Qualifying Change in Control Termination&#148;), the award vests in full. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-46-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Additionally, certain equity awards granted to members of our management
team continue to vest in accordance with the applicable vesting schedule after terminations of employment other than for cause. For example, pursuant to the terms of the employment agreements with each of Messrs. Coleman, Parratt and Primmer, upon a
termination by the Company without cause or a termination by the executive for good reason, the equity awards granted to such NEOs in July 2013 in connection with closing of the Mergers (or, for Mr.&nbsp;Parratt, the RSUs granted in January 2015 in
connection with his commencement of employment with the Company), continue to vest as if such executive&#146;s employment had continued, subject to compliance with non-competition and non-solicitation covenants as described above under
&#147;Agreements with our Named Executive Officers.&#148; Similarly, in the event each of Messrs. Coleman, Parratt, Primmer and Tusar terminate employment with the Company other than for good reason, RSUs granted to each such executive as a
component of his annual incentive compensation (for example, RSUs granted to NEOs in February 2014 (for the 2013 performance year), February 2015 (for the 2014 performance year) and February 2016 (for the 2015 performance year)) will continue to
vest as if such executive&#146;s employment had continued, subject to compliance with non-competition and non-solicitation covenants as described above under &#147;Agreements with our Named Executive Officers.&#148; We refer to this as treatment as
the &#147;Continued Vesting Provision,&#148; and in connection with the Equity Incentive Plan amendments approved by stockholders at our 2015 Annual Meeting, RSUs granted as a component of annual incentive compensation to all of our employees
(including Mr.&nbsp;Allison and Mr.&nbsp;Galvin) have this Continued Vesting Provision. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Applicable Definitions: Cause and Good Reason
</I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For the purposes of describing certain termination scenarios, &#147;cause&#148; and &#147;good
reason&#148; have the following definitions: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#147;Cause&#148; is generally defined in the employment
agreements with Messrs. Coleman, Parratt, Primmer and Tusar to mean a finding by the Board of any of the following: (A)&nbsp;continued and willful failure to perform substantially the executive&#146;s responsibilities, after demand for substantial
performance has been given by the Board, (B)&nbsp;illegal conduct, gross misconduct or gross neglect that caused material financial or reputational harm to the Company, (C)&nbsp;conviction of, or plea of guilty or nolo contendere to, a felony,
(D)&nbsp;a material breach of restrictive covenants in the executive&#146;s employment agreement after notice of, and a reasonable opportunity to cure the breach, (E)&nbsp;expulsion, or subjection to an order permanently or temporarily (more than 90
days) enjoining the executive, from the securities, investment management or investment banking business or the executive&#146;s disqualification or bar from acting in the capacity contemplated by the executive&#146;s employment agreement by the
Securities and Exchange Commission, the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority, any national securities exchange or any self-regulatory agency or governmental authority, in each case after all appeals have been exhausted or the executive has
admitted to such finding by consent, unless such expulsion, permanent injunction, disqualification or bar was due to the executive&#146;s engagement in conduct with the recorded authorization of the Board or in good faith, reasonable reliance on the
advice of the Company&#146;s counsel, (F)&nbsp;habitual abuse of narcotics or alcohol, (G)&nbsp;fraud or material dishonesty in connection with the Company&#146;s business, or (H)&nbsp;willful misappropriation of the Company&#146;s funds or
property. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Equity Incentive Plan provides that &#147;Cause&#148; has the meaning set forth in an
employment agreement or, in the case of Messrs. Galvin and Allison, to mean (A)&nbsp;a felony conviction, (B)&nbsp;the commission of an act of fraud or embezzlement against the Company, (C)&nbsp;willful misconduct or gross negligence materially
detrimental to the Company, (D)&nbsp;wrongful dissemination or use of confidential or proprietary information, or (E)&nbsp;the intentional and habitual neglect of duties to the Company. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#147;Good Reason&#148; is generally defined in the employment agreements with Messrs. Coleman, Parratt, Primmer and
Tusar to mean, without the executive&#146;s written consent, a material breach by the Company of the executive&#146;s employment agreement or of any other material financial obligation to the executive. For Messrs. Parratt, Primmer and Tusar,
&#147;good reason&#148; also includes a material diminution in duties, authority or responsibilities, for Messrs. Primmer and Tusar, &#147;good reason&#148; includes no longer reporting to Mr.&nbsp;Coleman (or his successor) and
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-47-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
the transfer of the executive&#146;s primary work site by more than 50 miles and for Mr.&nbsp;Primmer, &#147;good reason&#148; includes no longer being a member of the Company&#146;s management
committee. In order for a termination to constitute a termination for Good Reason, the executive must provide written notice to the Company of the existence of any event or condition that constitutes Good Reason within 90 days of its existence. Upon
receipt of such notice, the Company must be given 30 days to remedy such event or condition and the executive must terminate employment within 60 days following the last day of the Company&#146;s cure period. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_67"></A>2015 Table of Potential Payments Upon Termination and Change in Control </B></FONT></P>

other agreements described above (including the Equity Incentive Plan). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The amounts included in the tables

<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" BGCOLOR="#baedf7"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_69"></A>PROPOSAL 3&#151;RATIFICATION OF THE SELECTION OF
PRICEWATERHOUSECOOPERS LLP</B></FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The F&amp;A Committee has appointed PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP (&#147;PwC&#148;) as our
independent registered public accounting firm for the fiscal year ending December&nbsp;31, 2016. Additionally, the Board of Directors has ratified the appointment of PwC as our independent registered public accounting firm for the fiscal year ending
December&nbsp;31, 2016 and we are submitting the selection of PwC for stockholder ratification at the Annual Meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We expect that representatives of PwC will be present at the Annual Meeting to respond to appropriate questions, and they will have the opportunity to make a statement if they desire. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Although stockholder action on this matter is not required under our By-Laws or our Amended and Restated Certificate of
Incorporation, this appointment is being recommended to the stockholders for ratification because we believe it is a matter of good corporate practice. Unless contrary instructions are given, shares represented by proxies solicited by the Board will
be voted &#147;for&#148; the ratification of the selection of PwC as our independent registered public accountants for the year ending December&nbsp;31, 2016. If the selection of PwC is not ratified by the stockholders, the F&amp;A Committee will
reconsider whether or not to retain PwC, but still may retain them. Even if the selection of PwC is ratified, the F&amp;A Committee, in its discretion, may direct the appointment of a different independent registered public accounting firm at any
time during the year if it determines that such a change is in our best interests. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Adoption of this proposal
requires the affirmative vote of holders of a majority of the votes present in person or represented by proxy. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Board of Directors unanimously recommends that you vote &#147;<U>FOR</U>&#148; approval of PricewaterhouseCoopers
LLP as our independent registered public accounting firm for the year ending December&nbsp;31, 2016. </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Notwithstanding anything to the contrary set forth in any of our previous filings under the Securities Act, or the
Exchange Act, that incorporated future filings, including this Proxy Statement, the following section titled &#147;Report of the Finance and Audit Committee&#148; shall not be incorporated by reference into any such filings, except to the extent we
specifically incorporate such report by reference therein. </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_70"></A>REPORT OF THE FINANCE AND
AUDIT COMMITTEE </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2015, the F&amp;A Committee provided assistance to the Board of Directors in
fulfilling its oversight of: (1)&nbsp;the integrity of the financial statements and its risk and control environment; (2)&nbsp;the qualification of, and relationship with, the independent registered public accounting firm; (3)&nbsp;the
Company&#146;s internal audit function; (4)&nbsp;compliance with applicable legal and regulatory requirements; and (5)&nbsp;compliance with the Company&#146;s Code of Business Conduct and Ethics. The F&amp;A Committee also: (A)&nbsp;reviews and
makes recommendations to the Board regarding: (i)&nbsp;any proposed material capital formation plans including planned issuance of equity securities and debt instruments, and stock repurchase programs; and (ii)&nbsp;certain acquisitions,
investments, new business ventures, and divestitures by the Company; and (B)&nbsp;annually reviews and approves the Company&#146;s: (x)&nbsp;treasury investment policy outlining the general investment objectives of the Company and the specific
instruments for which investments are permitted; (y)&nbsp;liquidity risk management policy; and (z)&nbsp;contingency funding plan. The F&amp;A Committee currently operates under a written charter that was approved by the Board on March&nbsp;30, 2016
(the &#147;Charter&#148;). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The F&amp;A Committee is comprised of three independent Directors (Daniel Schmitt,
the Chairman, Alastair Rampell and Laurie Shahon). During 2015, Mr.&nbsp;James Milde served on the F&amp;A Committee through </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-52-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
December&nbsp;3, 2015. On December&nbsp;3, 2015, Mr.&nbsp;Rampell was appointed to the F&amp;A Committee and James Milde retired from the F&amp;A Committee in order to focus his efforts on
chairing the Compensation Committee and the Risk Committee. On April&nbsp;1, 2015, the Board determined, in its business judgment, that Mr.&nbsp;Schmitt was considered an &#147;audit committee financial expert&#148; as defined by the SOX Act. The
Board also determined at that time, in its business judgment, that Messrs. Schmitt and Milde and Ms.&nbsp;Shahon each complied with the applicable independence, experience and financial literacy requirements set forth by the NYSE, the SOX Act and
rules adopted by SEC pursuant to the SOX Act. The Board made the same determination for Mr.&nbsp;Rampell upon his joining the F&amp;A Committee on December&nbsp;3, 2015. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Management is responsible for the financial reporting process, including the system of internal control and the
preparation, presentation and integrity of the consolidated financial statements in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles. The independent registered public accounting firm is responsible for conducting an independent audit of the
financial statements in accordance with generally accepted auditing standards and evaluating the Company&#146;s internal controls, including management&#146;s assertion of the adequacy of its controls over financial reporting as required by
Section&nbsp;404 of the SOX Act. The F&amp;A Committee is responsible for monitoring and reviewing these processes. The F&amp;A Committee relies, without independent verification, on the information provided to it and on the representations made by
management and the independent registered public accounting firm. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2015, PwC was the Company&#146;s
independent registered public accounting firm, as ratified by the F&amp;A Committee on April&nbsp;1, 2015 and approved by the Company&#146;s stockholders at the 2015 Annual Meeting of Stockholders on May&nbsp;12, 2015. Notwithstanding that
ratification and stockholder approval, the F&amp;A Committee determined it would be in the Company&#146;s interest as a matter of good corporate governance to issue a request for proposal for audit services to PwC and certain other independent
registered public accounting firms. In response to its request, the F&amp;A Committee received written proposals from the four major public accounting firms. Each member of the F&amp;A Committee had the opportunity to extensively review the proposal
submissions in advance of their discussion of the proposals. The F&amp;A Committee, together with members of KCG&#146;s management, then met with representatives from three of the firms that submitted proposals to further evaluate each firm&#146;s
proposal and to ask questions regarding each firm&#146;s qualifications, industry experience, independence, systems to ensure audit quality and process for communication with the F&amp;A Committee. Following such meetings and upon review of the
proposals, on June&nbsp;12, 2015, the F&amp;A Committee reappointed PwC as the Company&#146;s auditor for 2015. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2015, the F&amp;A Committee received and reviewed the written disclosures and the letter from PwC required by
applicable requirements of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (&#147;PCAOB&#148;) regarding the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s communications with the F&amp;A Committee concerning auditor independence and held
discussions and reviewed with PwC all relationships it has with the Company to determine and satisfy itself regarding PwC&#146;s independence. When evaluating the independence of PwC, the F&amp;A Committee considered whether PwC&#146;s provision of
services to the Company beyond those rendered in connection with its audit and review of the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements was compatible with maintaining its objectivity and independence. The F&amp;A Committee reviewed and
approved, among other matters, the engagement of PwC for audit and non-audit services, and the amount of fees authorized for such services. All non-audit services performed by PwC were required to be pre-approved by the F&amp;A Committee or a
specified member thereof. The F&amp;A Committee also evaluated the qualifications and performance of PwC. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In
performing its duties, the F&amp;A Committee held 12 meetings during 2015 and met in executive session during both its regularly scheduled and special meetings. At each of its regularly scheduled meetings, the F&amp;A Committee held a joint meeting
with the Company&#146;s Risk Committee to discuss matters relating to the overlap between risk and internal control functions. Additionally, the F&amp;A Committee met in private session with the Chief Executive Officer, Chief Financial Officer,
General Counsel, Chief Risk Officer, Director of Internal Audit and PwC during various meetings held during 2015. These meetings were designed, among other things, to encourage free and open communications among the F&amp;A Committee, management and
PwC. PwC had free </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-53-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
access to the F&amp;A Committee to discuss any matters it deems appropriate. The F&amp;A Committee has discussed with PwC, with and without management present, the overall scope and plan for its
annual audit, the results of its examination and the overall quality of the Company&#146;s financial reporting and its evaluation of the Company&#146;s internal controls, including its assessment on management&#146;s assertion of the adequacy of its
controls over financial reporting as required by Section&nbsp;404 of the SOX Act. Additionally, the F&amp;A Committee discussed matters related to the conduct of the audit and other matters required to be discussed by PCAOB AU &#167;38
(Communication with Audit Committees). The F&amp;A Committee also reviewed and discussed the Form 10-K, the audited consolidated financial statements included therein for the fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, and Management&#146;s Report on
Internal Control over Financial Reporting with management and PwC. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2015, the F&amp;A Committee
performed all of its duties and responsibilities under the Charter. In addition, based on the F&amp;A Committee&#146;s discussions with management and PwC, review of the representations of management, including Management&#146;s Report on Internal
Control over Financial Reporting, and the report of PwC to the Board of Directors, and subject to the limitations on the role of the F&amp;A Committee referred to above and in the Charter, the F&amp;A Committee recommended to the Board of Directors
that the Company&#146;s audited consolidated financial statements for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 be included in the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Finance and Audit Committee </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Daniel F. Schmitt, Chairman </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Alastair Rampell </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Laurie M. Shahon </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_71"></A>AUDIT FEES, AUDIT-RELATED FEES, TAX FEES AND ALL OTHER FEES
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The F&amp;A Committee appointed PwC as our independent registered public accounting firm for the year
ending December&nbsp;31, 2016. We have been advised by PwC that it is an independent public accounting firm registered with the PCAOB and complies with the auditing, quality control and independence standards and rules of the PCAOB and the SEC.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The F&amp;A Committee appointed PwC as our independent registered public accounting firm for 2015.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As described in &#147;Report of the Finance and Audit Committee&#148; above, in 2015, in consideration of the
tenure of PwC as our independent registered public accounting firm (including its service to both predecessor entities, Knight and GETCO), the F&amp;A Committee engaged in an extensive process to solicit competitive proposals from firms to serve as
our independent public auditor for 2015, in order to review and evaluate the quality of service and comparability of available alternatives. At the request of the F&amp;A Committee, we submitted a request for proposal to several prominent registered
public accounting firms, including PwC, to act as our independent public auditor for 2015. In response to its request, the F&amp;A Committee received written proposals from four major public accounting firms. Each member of the F&amp;A Committee had
the opportunity to extensively review the proposal submissions in advance of their discussion of the proposals. The F&amp;A Committee, together with members of management, then met with representatives from three of the firms that submitted
proposals to further evaluate each firm&#146;s proposal and to ask questions regarding each firm&#146;s qualifications, industry experience, independence, systems to ensure audit quality and process for communication with the F&amp;A Committee.
Following such meetings and upon review of the proposals, on June&nbsp;12, 2015, the F&amp;A Committee reappointed PwC as the Company&#146;s auditor for 2015. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition to retaining PwC to audit the consolidated financial statements for 2015, we retained PwC, as well as other accounting and consulting firms, to provide various consulting services in 2015, and
we expect to continue to do so in the future. We understand the need for PwC to maintain its objectivity and independence in its audit of our financial statements, and therefore, we do not engage PwC for strategic consulting services, development of
tax planning transactions or for services prohibited by the SEC, such as internal audit work and financial information system design and implementation. We engage PwC for services outside of auditing financial statements when we conclude that
(i)&nbsp;PwC is the most appropriate provider of the relevant service and (ii)&nbsp;providing such service is not incompatible with PwC&#146;s maintenance of objectivity and independence. The following table reflects the fees earned by PwC for
services provided to KCG during 2014 and 2015: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_72"></A>PRE-APPROVAL POLICY FOR AUDIT AND NON-AUDIT SERVICES
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our F&amp;A Committee is responsible for appointing, setting compensation for and overseeing the work of
the independent registered public accounting firm. In addition, our F&amp;A Committee is responsible for pre-approving permitted non-audit services and fees to be performed by the independent registered public accounting firm and determine that such
services are compatible with maintaining its independence. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On an ongoing basis, our management communicates
specific projects and categories of service for which the advance approval of the F&amp;A Committee is requested. The F&amp;A Committee reviews these requests and advises management if the F&amp;A Committee approves the engagement of the independent
registered public accounting firm. The F&amp;A Committee may delegate to one or more of its members the authority to grant pre-approval required by this policy. On a periodic basis, our management reports to the F&amp;A Committee regarding the
actual spending for such projects and services compared to the pre-approved amounts. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In granting pre-approval
of certain non-audit services for 2015, the F&amp;A Committee considered whether the provision of such non-audit services rendered by our independent registered public accounting firm was compatible with maintaining their objectivity and
independence. The F&amp;A Committee concluded that such objectivity and independence would be maintained. For 2015, all of the fees associated with the independent registered public accounting firm services were pre-approved by the F&amp;A
Committee. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-56-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_73"></A>INFORMATION ON STOCK OWNERSHIP </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_74"></A>BENEFICIAL OWNERSHIP OF DIRECTORS, EXECUTIVE OFFICERS AND HOLDERS OF 5% OR MORE OF OUTSTANDING STOCK
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table sets forth, as of March&nbsp;28, 2016 certain information regarding the beneficial
ownership of the KCG Common Stock by: (i)&nbsp;each of KCG&#146;s named executive officers; (ii)&nbsp;each KCG director; (iii)&nbsp;each person who is known to KCG to own beneficially more than 5% of the KCG Common Stock; and (iv)&nbsp;the current
executive officers and directors of KCG as a group. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Such information is based, in part, upon information
provided by certain stockholders of KCG. In the case of persons other than the current executive officers and directors of KCG, such information is based on a review of Forms 4 and Schedules 13D and 13G filed with the SEC. As of March&nbsp;28, 2016,
there were 125 holders of record of KCG Common Stock and approximately 17,170 beneficial holders of KCG Common Stock. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_75"></A>SECTION&nbsp;16(A) BENEFICIAL OWNERSHIP REPORTING COMPLIANCE
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Exchange Act requires our directors and executive officers and any beneficial
owner of more than 10% of any class of our equity securities to file with the SEC initial reports of beneficial ownership and reports of changes in ownership of any of our securities. These reports are made on documents referred to as Forms 3, 4 and
5. Our directors and executive officers must also provide us with copies of these reports. We have reviewed the copies of the reports that we have received and written representations from the individuals required to file the reports. Based on this
review, we believe that during 2015 each of our directors and executive officers timely complied with applicable reporting requirements for transactions in our equity securities, except that one Form 4 on behalf of Stephen Schuler, filed on
May&nbsp;7, 2015 to report shares of KCG Common Stock sold by Mr.&nbsp;Schuler on May&nbsp;1, 2015, was inadvertently filed late due to a technical error. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-60-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_76"></A>ANNUAL MEETING INFORMATION </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board of Directors is soliciting your proxy for our 2016 Annual Meeting of Stockholders and any adjournment of the
meeting, for the purposes set forth in the Notice of Annual Meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_77"></A>Notice and Access of Proxy Materials
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">To expedite delivery, reduce our costs and decrease the environmental impact of our proxy materials, we
have elected, in accordance with the SEC&#146;s &#147;Notice and Access&#148; rule, to deliver the Notice to our stockholders and to provide proxy materials to our stockholder over the Internet. The Notice is being mailed on April&nbsp;1, 2016 to
all of our stockholders who have not requested a paper or electronic copy of our proxy materials. This Proxy Statement and our 2015 Annual Report on Form 10-K will first be made available to our stockholders on or about that date. If you received a
Notice, you will not receive a printed copy of the proxy materials in the mail. Instead, the Notice instructs you on how to access and review all of the important information contained in the proxy materials and how to submit your proxy via the
Internet or by mail. If you received a Notice and would like to receive a copy of our proxy materials, follow the instructions contained in the Notice to obtain a copy electronically or request a copy in paper form, which will include a proxy card
or voting instruction form, on a one-time or ongoing basis at no charge. We will not mail a paper copy of the Proxy Statement and Annual Report to you unless specifically requested to do so. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_78"></A>Who Can Vote; Outstanding Shares on Record Date </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Only stockholders of record of the KCG Common Stock at the close of business on March&nbsp;15, 2016, which we refer to as the &#147;record date,&#148; may vote at the Annual Meeting. On the record date,
we had 83,467,135 shares of KCG Common Stock outstanding (excluding (i)&nbsp;RSUs, which do not have voting rights, (ii)&nbsp;KCG Common Stock held in our treasury and (iii)&nbsp;outstanding warrants to purchase KCG Common Stock). You are entitled
to one vote for each share of KCG Common Stock that you owned on the record date. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_79"></A>What Is a Proxy?
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Your proxy gives us authority to vote your shares and tells us how to vote your shares at the Annual
Meeting or any adjournment. Two of our employees, who are called &#147;proxies&#148; or &#147;proxy holders&#148; and are named on the proxy card, will vote your shares at the Annual Meeting according to the instructions you give on the proxy card
or by telephone or over the Internet. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_80"></A>Voting Your Shares; Revoking Your Proxy </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Your vote is important. Whether or not you plan to attend the Annual Meeting, we encourage you to vote your shares
promptly. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">You may vote in any of the following four ways: (i)&nbsp;by attending the Annual Meeting;
(ii)&nbsp;by calling the toll-free telephone number listed on the proxy card; (iii)&nbsp;by voting on the Internet at the website address listed on the Notice or proxy card; or (iv)&nbsp;if you requested a paper copy of this Proxy Statement, by
marking, signing, dating and mailing your proxy card in the postage-paid envelope provided or return it to Vote Processing, c/o Broadridge, 51 Mercedes Way, Edgewood, New York 11717. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-61-
</FONT></P>

instructions for any particular matter or matters, shares of KCG Common Stock represented by such proxy will be voted as follows: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

Annual Meeting other than as described herein. If, however, other matters are properly brought before the Annual Meeting or any adjournments or postponements thereof, the persons appointed as proxies will have the discretion to vote or act thereon
in accordance with their best judgment, unless authority to do so is withheld in the proxy. Any proxy given pursuant to this solicitation may be revoked by the person giving it at any time before the shares of KCG Common Stock represented by such
proxy are voted at the Annual Meeting by: (i)&nbsp;attending and voting in person at the Annual Meeting; (ii)&nbsp;giving notice of revocation of the proxy at the Annual Meeting; (iii)&nbsp;submitting a proxy relating to the same shares and matters
to be considered at the Annual Meeting (by telephone, by Internet or by submitting a paper proxy card) on a later date than the proxy previously submitted or (iv)&nbsp;delivering a written notice of revocation to the Corporate Secretary of KCG.
Attendance at the Annual Meeting will not in and of itself constitute a revocation of a proxy. All written notices of revocation and other communications with respect to the revocation of proxies should be addressed as follows: KCG Holdings, Inc.,
545 Washington Boulevard, Jersey City, New Jersey 07310, Attention: Corporate Secretary, and must be received before the taking of the votes at the Annual Meeting. If you own shares of KCG Common Stock held in street name and wish to vote at the
Annual Meeting, you must have a legal proxy from your broker. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_81"></A>Annual Meeting Admission </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">All stockholders will need to present photo identification to be admitted into the Annual Meeting. Beneficial owners of
stock held by banks, brokers or investment plans (in &#147;street name&#148;) will also need proof of ownership. A recent brokerage statement or letter or legal proxy from your broker or bank are examples of proof of ownership. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx129066_82"></A>Quorum </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">A quorum is the minimum number of shares required to conduct business at the Annual Meeting. Under our By-Laws, to have a quorum, a majority of the issued and outstanding shares of stock entitled to vote
at the Annual Meeting must be represented in person or by proxy at the meeting. Shares of KCG Common Stock represented by proxies that are marked &#147;Abstain&#148; and broker non-votes will be counted as shares of KCG Common Stock present for
purposes of determining the presence of a quorum on all matters, but will not, unless otherwise noted herein, be counted as votes cast in favor of the matters brought before the stockholders at the Annual Meeting. In the event a quorum is not
present at the Annual Meeting, we expect that the Annual Meeting will be adjourned or postponed to solicit additional proxies. </FONT></P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">If your shares are held through a broker, the broker will ask you how you want your
shares to be voted. If you give the broker instructions, your shares will be voted as you direct. If you do not give instructions, pursuant to NYSE rules, if you own your shares of KCG Common Stock through a broker and you do not vote, your broker
may vote your shares of KCG Common Stock at its discretion on certain &#147;routine&#148; matters. KCG believes that all of the matters to be voted upon at the Annual Meeting, except for the ratification of the appointment of PwC as KCG&#146;s
independent registered public accounting firm for 2016, are not considered &#147;routine&#148; matters under NYSE rules, and therefore, brokers will not be permitted to vote, at their discretion, any unvoted shares on those proposals (reported as a
broker non-vote). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following summarizes your choices for casting your vote on each matter to be voted upon
